\title{Whisper-λ: sealed-sender slice}
\taxon{implementation}
\date{2026-05-15}
\author{eternal-loop}
\tag{whisper-lambda}
\tag{sealed-sender}
\tag{captp}
\tag{syrup}
\tag{vertical-slice}

\p{First implementation vertical slice for [[bcf-0064]]. Validates that captp+syrup can carry Signal-style sealed-sender envelopes without requiring X3DH or the Double Ratchet to exist. If this slice doesn't fit, the entire transport choice in bcf-0064 must be revisited.}

\subtree{
\title{Why this slice first}
\ul{
\li{It is \em{the bet}: the design's distinguishing claim is that captp's sealed/sturdy/revocable primitives subsume Signal's hand-rolled sealed-sender envelope mechanism. Either captp gives this for free, or it doesn't.}
\li{No prerequisite crypto state machine — no ratchet, no X3DH. Just one envelope, one round trip.}
\li{Failure here is a transport-axis falsification, not a coding slog. We get an early signal on the riskiest assumption.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Effect signature sketch (Effekt-flavored pseudosyntax)}
\pre{\startverb
effect SealedSender {
  def seal(payload: Bytes^1, recipient: SwissNum): SealedEnvelope^1
  def unseal(env: SealedEnvelope^1, my_swiss: SwissNum^1): (SenderSwiss, Bytes^1)
}

// Grade ^1 = used at most once. The ephemeral sender key inside seal()
// is grade ^1; it must not leak out of the sealed envelope.
//
// The unseal handler is *shallow*: it resumes the caller with the
// (sender, payload) pair exactly once; no captured continuation lingers.

handler captp_sealed_sender = SealedSender {
  def seal(payload, recipient) = {
    let eph = generate_keypair()        // eph.priv : Bytes^1
    let shared = x25519(eph.priv, recipient.pubkey)
    let aead_key = hkdf(shared, "ss-aead-v1")
    let ct = aead_seal(aead_key, payload, AD=eph.pub ++ recipient.swiss)
    resume(SealedEnvelope { eph_pub: eph.pub, ct: ct })
    // eph.priv falls out of scope; Granule's grade ≤1 + drop = zeroize
  }
  def unseal(env, my_swiss) = {
    let shared = x25519(my_swiss.priv, env.eph_pub)
    let aead_key = hkdf(shared, "ss-aead-v1")
    let payload = aead_open(aead_key, env.ct, AD=env.eph_pub ++ my_swiss.pub)
    let sender = recover_sender_from_signature(payload)
    resume((sender, strip_sender_sig(payload)))
  }
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Syrup wire format}
\p{One record, no schemas required — syrup is self-describing.}
\pre{\startverb
sealed-envelope = <record sealed-envelope-v1
                    <eph-pub Bytes32>
                    <ct Bytes>>
\stopverb}
\p{eph-pub is 32 bytes (X25519). ct is the AEAD ciphertext (AD = eph-pub ++ recipient swissnum). No length prefix needed; syrup's record encoding is self-delimiting.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Test vector sources}
\ul{
\li{\strong{libsignal-rust} sealed-sender tests (file: \code{signal-protocol/tests/sealed_sender.rs}) — extract the (eph-priv, recipient-priv, plaintext, ciphertext) tuples, re-encode in syrup, expect bit-identical AEAD output for a chosen test vector.}
\li{Wycheproof X25519+HKDF+AEAD vectors — apply at the primitive level before composing the envelope.}
\li{Property test: \code{forall msg, recip. unseal(seal(msg, recip)) ≡ (sender, msg)} — under Hypothesis-style generation with Hedgehog-style shrinking.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Pass criteria for iter8}
\ol{
\li{Wycheproof X25519 + HKDF-SHA256 + AES-GCM-SIV all pass via FFI shim.}
\li{Syrup encode/decode round-trip property check passes.}
\li{One libsignal-rust sealed-sender vector decodes bit-identically through the captp_sealed_sender handler.}
\li{The shallow-handler invariant holds: no captured continuation references the ephemeral private key after seal() returns.}
}
\p{If 1+2 pass but 3 fails, the gap is the AD construction or sender-signature framing — recoverable. If 4 fails, the handler discipline is wrong — back to bcf-0064.}
}

